### History

The genesis of [Wrexham County Borough Council](/Wrexham_County_Borough_Council_elections) can be traced back to the grand bureaucratic reshuffle of 1996, a direct consequence of the [Local Government (Wales) Act 1994](/Local_Government_(Wales)_Act_1994). This legislative act, designed to streamline—or perhaps merely rearrange—local administration across [Wales](/Wales), saw the creation of new principal areas. For [Wrexham](/Wrexham), this meant the formation of a new county borough, which, with a certain administrative neatness, absorbed the entirety of the former [district](/Districts_of_Wales) of [Wrexham Maelor](/Wrexham_Maelor). Not content with just one former entity, it also assimilated a rather modest portion of the [Glyndŵr](/Glynd%C5%B5r_(district)) district. Both of these territories had previously fallen under the jurisdiction of the now-defunct county of [Clwyd](/Clwyd).

On the first day of April 1996, a date perhaps chosen for its symbolic association with new beginnings (or elaborate jokes, depending on your perspective), the new [Wrexham County Borough Council](/Wrexham_County_Borough_Council_elections) officially commenced operations. It seamlessly—or so the records claim—inherited the responsibilities that had previously been fragmented between the county-level functions of [Clwyd County Council](/Clwyd_County_Council) and the more localised district-level duties of the two aforementioned district councils. These predecessor bodies, having served their purpose, were promptly abolished, making way for the new, unified authority. &#91;3&#93;

In a rather recent development, on 1 September 2022, the county borough found itself elevated to the esteemed rank of a city. This bestowal of [city status](/City_status_in_the_United_Kingdom) often comes with a certain civic pride and, occasionally, a new set of stationery. Curiously, despite this prestigious upgrade, the council has opted to retain its original, somewhat more provincial, designation, continuing to style itself "Wrexham County Borough Council." One might speculate on the reasons for this, perhaps a fondness for tradition, or simply an admirable resistance to unnecessary rebranding efforts. &#91;4&#93;

In a more earthly matter, related to the very practicalities of governance, councillors' compensation was a topic of discussion in November 2023. At that time, the annual basic salary for a councillor stood at £17,600. The council, ever mindful of the cost of living (or perhaps just the value of their own time), put forward a proposal for a 6% increase, which would see the basic salary rise to £18,666. A modest sum, perhaps, for navigating the labyrinthine corridors of local politics. &#91;5&#93;

### Political control

Since the turn of the millennium, or more precisely, since 1999, the council has been operating in a state of perpetual political equipoise, characterised by [no overall control](/No_overall_control). This means no single party has managed to secure an outright majority, leading to the intriguing, if sometimes frustrating, dance of coalition-building and shifting allegiances.

Following the most recent electoral contest, the [2022 election](/2022_Wrexham_County_Borough_Council_election), the administration of the council settled into a coalition arrangement. This current governing bloc is primarily composed of the "Independent Group," a significant faction encompassing 21 of the council's independent councillors, who have chosen to align themselves with the [Conservative](/Welsh_Conservatives) group. &#91;6&#93; Demonstrating the fluid nature of local politics, the council's sole [Liberal Democrat](/Welsh_Liberal_Democrats) councillor made the strategic decision to join this administration in December 2022, solidifying the coalition's position, at least for the time being. &#91;7&#93;

The inaugural election for this iteration of the council took place in 1995. This was a transitional period, with the newly elected body functioning as a "shadow authority." It was a probationary phase, if you will, allowing it to prepare for its full operational powers, which were formally granted on 1 April 1996. The trajectory of political control since that founding date has been, predictably, varied: &#91;8&#93;

| Party in control | Years |
| :--------------- | :---- |
| [Labour](/Welsh_Labour) | 1996–1999 |
| [No overall control](/No_overall_control) | 1999–present |

This persistent state of "no overall control" since 1999 suggests a deeply fractured local political landscape, where consensus is often hard-won and majorities are always provisional. It’s a testament to the diverse, and sometimes stubbornly independent, political leanings of the [Wrexham](/Wrexham) electorate.

