The term "Independent" in local government often serves as a broad umbrella, encompassing a spectrum of political leanings and affiliations. In [Wrexham](/Wrexham), this is particularly evident. Of the 26 councillors who identify as [Independent](/Independent_politician), a substantial bloc of 21 have coalesced to form the "Independent Group." This group is notable for its alliance with the single [Liberal Democrat](/Welsh_Liberal_Democrats) councillor, forming a key part of the current administration. Beyond this primary grouping, two other independents have chosen to band together, forming the "Progressive Independent" group, adding another layer of nuance to the council's political ecosystem. The remaining three independent councillors, perhaps valuing their autonomy above all, do not belong to any formal group, preferring to navigate the political landscape unaligned. &#91;27&#93; This fragmentation underscores the challenge of establishing stable, majority rule in the council. The next opportunity for a potential shift in this delicate balance is anticipated with the next scheduled election in 2027. &#91;28&#93;

