### Premises

The administrative nerve centre of [Wrexham County Borough Council](/Wrexham_County_Borough_Council_elections) is the [Guildhall](/Wrexham_Guildhall), a structure that stands with a certain mid-century gravitas off Rhosddu Road, right in the heart of [Wrexham](/Wrexham). It presides over the relatively tranquil open expanse of [Llwyn Isaf](/Llwyn_Isaf), offering a view that is perhaps more pastoral than one might expect from a seat of local power.

This particular incarnation of the [Guildhall](/Wrexham_Guildhall) was constructed between 1959 and 1961, a period when architectural design often leaned towards a robust, functional aesthetic. It was originally commissioned for the then-active Wrexham Borough Council, a predecessor body in the ever-shifting administrative landscape. Following further reorganisations, it subsequently served as the official headquarters for [Wrexham Maelor](/Wrexham_Maelor) Borough Council, a role it fulfilled from 1974 until 1996. It was at this juncture, in 1996, that the current [Wrexham County Borough Council](/Wrexham_County_Borough_Council_elections) was established, inheriting not just the administrative functions, but also the physical premises, continuing a tradition of housing local governance within its walls. &#91;33&#93; The building, therefore, has witnessed several iterations of local authority, a silent observer to the ebb and flow of regional power.

### Electoral divisions

For a more granular understanding of local representation, one might consult the [List of electoral wards in Wrexham County Borough](/List_of_electoral_wards_in_Wrexham_County_Borough). The [Wrexham County Borough](/Wrexham_County_Borough) is meticulously carved into forty-nine distinct [electoral wards](/Electoral_wards), each designed to return a specific number of councillors, culminating in a total of fifty-six representatives. This intricate system ensures that various local areas have their voices heard within the council chamber.

Further complicating, or perhaps enriching, this administrative tapestry are the 35 [communities](/Community_(Wales)) that exist within the county borough. A significant number of these communities possess their own elected councils, operating at an even more localised level, providing an additional layer of governance and representation. It’s a multi-tiered approach, designed to capture the nuances of local needs and aspirations, though one might occasionally question the efficiency of such a layered structure.

