### History

The genesis of [Wrexham County Borough Council](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wrexham_County_Borough_Council_elections) can be traced back to the grand bureaucratic reshuffle of 1996, a direct consequence of the [Local Government (Wales) Act 1994](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Local_Government_(Wales)_Act_1994). This legislative act, designed to streamline—or perhaps merely rearrange—local administration across [Wales](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wales), saw the creation of new principal areas. For [Wrexham](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wrexham), this meant the formation of a new county borough, which, with a certain administrative neatness, absorbed the entirety of the former [district](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Districts_of_Wales) of [Wrexham Maelor](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wrexham_Maelor). Not content with just one former entity, it also assimilated a rather modest portion of the [Glyndŵr](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Glynd%C5%B5r_(district)) district, specifically areas like the community of [Glyntraian](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Glyntraian) and parts of [Llangollen Rural](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Llangollen_Rural). Both of these territories had previously fallen under the jurisdiction of the now-defunct county of [Clwyd](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Clwyd), which itself was created in 1974.

On the first day of April 1996, a date perhaps chosen for its symbolic association with new beginnings (or elaborate jokes, depending on your perspective), the new [Wrexham County Borough Council](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wrexham_County_Borough_Council_elections) officially commenced operations. It seamlessly—or so the records claim—inherited the responsibilities that had previously been fragmented between the county-level functions of [Clwyd County Council](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Clwyd_County_Council) and the more localised district-level duties from the two aforementioned district councils, [Wrexham Maelor](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wrexham_Maelor) and [Glyndŵr](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Glynd%C5%B5r_(district)). These predecessor bodies, having served their purpose in the intricate dance of Welsh local government, were promptly abolished, making way for the new, unified authority. This restructuring aimed to create more efficient and locally accountable administrative units, replacing the two-tier system with unitary authorities. &#91;3&#93;

In a rather recent development, on 1 September 2022, the county borough found itself elevated to the esteemed rank of a city. This bestowal of [city status](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/City_status_in_the_United_Kingdom) often comes with a certain civic pride and, occasionally, a new set of stationery. It was granted as part of the Platinum Jubilee celebrations of Queen Elizabeth II, a competitive process where 39 towns across the UK applied. Curiously, despite this prestigious upgrade, the council has opted to retain its original, somewhat more provincial, designation, continuing to style itself "Wrexham County Borough Council." One might speculate on the reasons for this, perhaps a fondness for tradition, an aversion to unnecessary rebranding efforts, or simply the recognition that the fundamental administrative functions remain unchanged regardless of the titular upgrade. &#91;4&#93;

In a more earthly matter, related to the very practicalities of governance, councillors' compensation was a topic of discussion in November 2023. At that time, the annual basic salary for a councillor stood at £17,600, a figure set by the Independent Remuneration Panel for Wales. The council, ever mindful of the cost of living (or perhaps just the perceived value of their own time and increased responsibilities), put forward a proposal for a 6% increase, which would see the basic salary rise to £18,666. A modest sum, perhaps, for navigating the labyrinthine corridors of local politics, attending numerous meetings, and representing diverse constituents, especially when compared to salaries in other sectors. &#91;5&#93;

### Political control

Since the turn of the millennium, or more precisely, since 1999, the council has been operating in a state of perpetual political equipoise, characterised by [no overall control](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/No_overall_control). This means no single party has managed to secure an outright majority, leading to the intriguing, if sometimes frustrating, dance of coalition-building and shifting allegiances that has become a hallmark of [Wrexham](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wrexham)'s local governance. This fragmented political landscape often necessitates complex negotiations and compromises to form an administration capable of making decisions.

Following the most recent electoral contest, the [2022 election](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2022_Wrexham_County_Borough_Council_election), the administration of the council settled into a coalition arrangement. This current governing bloc is primarily composed of the "Independent Group," a significant faction encompassing 21 of the council's independent councillors, who have chosen to align themselves with the [Conservative](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Welsh_Conservatives) group, which holds 8 seats. &#91;6&#93; Demonstrating the fluid nature of local politics, the council's sole [Liberal Democrat](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Welsh_Liberal_Democrats) councillor made the strategic decision to join this administration in December 2022, further solidifying the coalition's position, at least for the time being. This move increased the administration's total count to 30 councillors out of 56, providing a working but not overwhelming majority. &#91;7&#93;

The inaugural election for this iteration of the council took place in 1995. This was a transitional period, with the newly elected body functioning as a "shadow authority." It was a probationary phase, if you will, allowing it to prepare for its full operational powers, which were formally granted on 1 April 1996. During this shadow period, councillors could plan and establish the necessary structures before officially taking over from the abolished authorities. The trajectory of political control since that founding date has been, predictably, varied, showcasing the diverse political leanings within the county borough: &#91;8&#93;

| Party in control | Years |
| :--------------- | :---- |
| [Labour](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Welsh_Labour) | 1996–1999 |
| [No overall control](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/No_overall_control) | 1999–present |

This persistent state of "no overall control" since 1999 suggests a deeply fractured local political landscape, where consensus is often hard-won and majorities are always provisional. It’s a testament to the diverse, and sometimes stubbornly independent, political leanings of the [Wrexham](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wrexham) electorate, which has consistently refused to grant a single party outright dominance for over two decades. This requires continuous negotiation and compromise, making the governance of the council a delicate balancing act.

### Leadership

In the grand scheme of local governance, the role of [Mayor of Wrexham](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mayor_of_Wrexham) is, to put it mildly, largely ceremonial. It's a position steeped in tradition and civic representation, involving ribbon-cutting and pleasantries, chairing council meetings, and acting as the first citizen of the county borough, but wielding little in the way of direct political power. The actual, gritty business of political leadership falls squarely upon the shoulders of the [leader of the council](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Leader_of_the_council). This individual navigates the choppy waters of council meetings, coalition demands, public expectations, and the implementation of policy.

